passages.text: Top line growth with positive traffic, while operating margins came in below expectations; FY25 guidance raised at the midpoint
BBWI12m Price Target: $39.00Price: $29.36Upside: 32.8%

BBWI closed down \(6.9\%\) (vs. the S&P \(+0.3\%\) ) following its 2Q miss and higher FY25 guidance. We think some of the weakness in the stock could be attributed to the rare miss on operating margins with SG&A coming in much higher than expected. The company also introduced 3Q25 guidance, which came in below consensus (LSEG Data & Analytics) expectations. That said, in our view, the stock reaction seems overdone today, noting our FY25 EPS estimate is only moving down \(\sim 1\%\) . We would also highlight that gross margin came in above expectations, with mix-adjusted AUR growing LSD in 2Q, while SG&A was pressured due to higher selling expenses. We remain positive on BBWI given the company is well positioned to provide customers with value by offering affordable luxuries, along with the number of initiatives the company has for growth, including its robust pipeline of product ideas, newness, collaborations, and growth in category adjacencies, and an increase in personalized marketing. Additionally, we view the valuation as highly attractive with the stock trading at 8.0x NTM P/E. We reiterate our Buy rating with a 12- month price target of \$39.

2Q comp growth driven by traffic and the semi- annual sale: 2Q sales came in up \(1.5\%\) y/y, driven by positive dual- channel traffic and led by the company's semi- annual sale performance. Soaps & sanitizers was up HSD, noting the sanitizer business performed above the shop with customers responding positively to new products (i.e., moisturizing Pocketbacs and 1oz sanitizer spray). Home fragrance came in up LSD, driven by single wick candles, Wallflowers, car fragrance, and home sprays. Body care was the weakest of the core categories, coming in down LSD, with performance driven by a soft Mother's Day, which was offset by growth in men's (which the company highlighted

during Father's Day). BBWI's semi- annual sale (SAS) benefited from a strategic shift in timing back 2 weeks, along with the right mix of product and clear signaling around the event. On 8/18, BBWI introduced the Disney Villains Collection (available to loyalty members on 3/26- 27 and to all customers on 9/3) and announced a longer- term relationship between Bath & Body Works and Disney, noting on the call that the companies have entered into a multi- year partnership. Collaborations can get customers into the store during lull periods and drive excitement outside of the holidays, which we see as an important driver going forward. We would also flag that in 1Q, BBWI's Disney Princess collaboration exceeded internal expectations and drove growth in body care. In terms of cadence, May was softer (largely impacted by the timing of the SAS), June was strong from a sales and traffic perspective, and July was more back to normal (when normalized for the Halloween launch and Prime Days). Looking to 3Q, key performance drivers include the Disney Villains launch, fall assortment, and a single fragrance launch which will come at the end of the quarter.

Operating margins pressured by SG&A deleverage: Gross margin for 2Q came in at \(41.3\%\) ( \(+30\) bps y/y) and above consensus at \(41.1\%\) , with leverage resulting from B&O, largely due to the exit of a third- party fulfillment center. The company also called out a \(\) 16\mathrm{mn}\(or\) \sim 100\$ bps) tariff headwind. In 2Q, BBWI's mix- adjusted AUR came in up LSD, consistent with 1Q trends. Per management, BBWI was less promotional overall for the quarter, despite a large sales mix into the SAS time frame. That said, looking at SG&A, expense dollars tracked \(5.6\%\) higher y/y, and the expense ratio came in at \(30.2\%\) ( \(+110\) bps y/y), above consensus at \(29.9\%\) , with deleverage driven by selling expenses, including investments in new stores and higher healthcare costs.

FY25 guidance narrowed and raised at the midpoint, while 3Q outlook came in below expectations: BBWI updated its outlook for FY25 and is now guiding to net sales of \(+1.5 - 2.7\%\) , up from \(+1 - 3\%\) prior. The company's updated guidance reflects its 1H performance along with consistent expectations for \(+1 - 3\%\) net sales growth in 2H. BBWI is also guiding to a gross margin of \(- 44\%\) and an SG&A rate of \(- 27.7\%\) for the year. The company expects tariffs to negatively impact gross profit by \(- \updownarrow 85\mathrm{mn}\) (net of mitigation efforts), noting that most of the impact was not included in its initial February guidance. On SG&A, BBWI expects to continue investing in technology, with spend up modestly y/y, and is continuing marketing investments \((- 3.5\%\) of net sales). Additionally, BBWI is guiding to an EPS of \(\) 3.35- 3.60\((vs. consensus at\) \ \(3.46\) ), which includes the anticipated impact of \(\) 400\mathrm{mn}\(of cash used for share repurchases, up from\) \ \(300\mathrm{mn}\) prior. BBWI also introduced 3Q25 guidance, which came in below consensus expectations, including net sales of \(+1 - 3\%\) , versus consensus at \(+1.7\%\) . We would note that BBWI should benefit in 2H from additional collaborations (e.g., Disney Villains), along with improvements in its digital business, including the launch of a new app in September and a relaunch of mobile web starting in October. Additionally, BBWI's launch in over 600 college campus stores provides an opportunity to get in front of a younger consumer, and we will likely see additional opportunities for expanded distribution in the future as well. For 3Q, BBWI is guiding to a gross margin of \(- 42.2\%\) , an SG&A rate of \(- 31.5\%\) , and EPS in the range of \(\) 0.37- 0.45\((vs. consensus at\) \ \(0.49\) ). In terms of tariff impacts, \(- \updownarrow 40\mathrm{mn}\) is
included in 3Q as it was disproportionately impacted by inventory receipts subject to the \(145\%\) China tariff rate.

Following 2Q25 results, we lower our FY25 net sales growth estimate to \(+2.6\%\) (from \(+2.7\%\) ), while we lower our gross margin estimate to \(44.4\%\) (from \(44.5\%\) ). Our FY25 EPS estimate decreases to \(\) 3.55\(from\) \ \(3.59\) , and our FY26/FY27 estimates decrease \(\sim 1\%\) to \(\) 3.94/\(\) 4.31\(, respectively.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.
